To determine the fluorescence quenching modes, the fluorescence lifetime recognized as a general criterion to primarily distinguish between static or dynamic pathways were measured. From Fig. 8c–d, the fluorescence lifetime of Si-CDs (13.4 ns) was almost the same as the Si-CDs-Fe3+ system (14.4 ns), indicting the static quenching between Si-CDs and Fe3+ due to the strong affinity between the half-filled 3 d orbital of Fe3+ and some electron-rich groups. The actual fluorescence quenching mechanism was further studied according to the Stern–Volmer equation [39] and Benesi–Hildebrand's equation [45] (Fig. 8e and f). From Fig. 8e, the regression equation can be expressed as follows: F0/F-1 = 0.00855CFe
                        3+. The quenching constant (Ksv) value is determined as 0.00855 μmol/L−1. The quenching rate constant (Kq) is 6.4 × 1011(mol/L)−1S−1 based on the fluorescence lifetime of Si-CDs (13.389 ns). The Kq of dynamic quenching is less than 1.0 × 1010(mol/L)−1S−1. Therefore, the resulted Kq suggests a static quenching rather than a dynamic quenching. Moreover, the number of binding sites (n) and binding constant (K) could be obtained according to the slope and intercept of Benesi–Hildebrand's equation. The binding sites (n) and binding constant (K) were calculated to 0.8 and 1.12 × 103 mol/L. Moreover, there is a spectrum overlap between the absorption of Si-CDs and Fe3+ (Fig. 8g), and no other different peak appears upon the addition of Fe3+(Fig. 8h), which possibly suggests the fluorescence quenching of Si-CDs by Fe3+ is originated from the internal filtering effect (Fig. 9
                        ) [38,46].
